<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
The distribution range of this species (northern Brazil, on the border with Venezuela and Guyanas) represents the northernmost distribution compared to the aforementioned species and subspecies. It is likely that 
<bibRefCitation author="Endroedi, S" journalOrPublisher="Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="37 - 86" refId="B13" refString="Endroedi, S, 1977. Monographie der Dynastinae. (Coleoptera) 6. Tribus Dynastini II. Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae 23: 37 - 86" title="Monographie der Dynastinae. (Coleoptera) 6. Tribus Dynastini II." volume="23" year="1977">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Endrödi’s">Endroedi's</normalizedToken>
(1977)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.1037.1.3" author="Moron, MA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="29 - 36" refId="B28" refString="Moron, MA, 2005. A new species of Megasoma Kirby (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Dynastinae) from Sinaloa, Mexico. Zootaxa 1037: 29 - 36, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.1037.1.3" title="A new species of Megasoma Kirby (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Dynastinae) from Sinaloa, Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.1037.1.3" volume="1037" year="2005">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Morón’s">Moron's</normalizedToken>
(2005)
</bibRefCitation>
claims of the alleged presence of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. gyas" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="gyas">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">M. gyas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Suriname and Guyana refer to this species. The validity of this taxon has been recently confirmed by further findings from Venezuela, at the border with Brazil (see Kobayashi, 2019). Only ten specimens have been collected thus far and a large specimen is deposited in MSNM. It is a completely glabrous 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Megasoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megasoma" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Megasoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on its dorsal side. Ventrally it bears a very poor pubescence, mainly on female specimens. The variability of total body length varies from 68 to 105 mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 29" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 29. A M. hermes ♂ B M. hermes ♀." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.53130.figure29" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481454" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">29</figureCitation>
, courtesy Mushi-sha).
</paragraph>
